3:["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Paradex calculates funding rates hourly using a TWAP-based mechanism that compares the perpetual price to the underlying JUP spot index. Funding payments occur automatically at the top of each hour, with rates typically ranging from -0.5% to +0.5% annually. The platform's StarkNet infrastructure enables gas-efficient position management, though traders must account for StarkNet's block confirmation times. Portfolio margin capabilities allow for capital-efficient multi-position strategies across available pairs."}]
4:["$","section",null,{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":["Why ","JUP","/","USDT","?"]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"JUP/USDT represents one of the few Jupiter perpetual offerings in the DEX space, making it valuable for traders seeking exposure outside centralized exchanges. The pair's mid-tier volume creates opportunities for funding rate inefficiencies, particularly during Solana ecosystem volatility. Jupiter's role as a key Solana DeFi aggregator often drives correlated movements with broader Solana DeFi sentiment."}]]}]
5:["$","section","0",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Historical Rate Patterns"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"JUP funding rates on Paradex have shown elevated volatility during major Solana ecosystem events and Jupiter airdrop announcements. The 1-hour funding cycle creates more granular rate adjustments compared to 8-hour systems, with rates frequently oscillating between positive and negative throughout volatile trading sessions. Peak funding events typically coincide with significant JUP spot price movements exceeding 10% daily ranges. The DEX structure means rates can deviate more significantly from CEX equivalents, especially during periods of concentrated StarkNet network activity."}]]}]
6:["$","section","1",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Arbitrage Opportunities"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"Cross-exchange arbitrage between Paradex and major CEXs becomes viable when funding rate differentials exceed transaction costs and StarkNet bridging fees. The platform's self-custodial nature eliminates counterparty risk but requires careful management of StarkNet gas costs and bridge timing. Intra-hour rate adjustments can create micro-arbitrage opportunities for sophisticated traders with automated systems. Portfolio margin enables capital-efficient hedging strategies using correlated Solana ecosystem pairs when available."}]]}]
7:["$","section","2",{"className":"mb-10","children":[["$","h2",null,{"className":"text-2xl font-extrabold tracking-tight text-foreground mt-12 mb-4","style":{"fontFamily":"var(--font-montserrat), sans-serif"},"children":"Risk Considerations"}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-muted-foreground leading-relaxed","children":"StarkNet's relative immaturity introduces additional technical risks including potential network congestion and bridge vulnerabilities. Paradex's early-stage status means limited liquidity depth and wider bid-ask spreads during volatile periods. The minimal pair coverage restricts hedging options compared to established platforms. Traders must factor StarkNet withdrawal times into risk management, as immediate position unwinding may be constrained during network stress. Smart contract risks inherent to DEX operations require additional due diligence compared to regulated exchanges."}]]}]
8:["$","$Ld",null,{"items":[{"question":"How do JUP funding rates on Paradex compare to centralized exchanges?","answer":"Paradex typically shows higher funding rate volatility due to its DEX structure and 1-hour intervals versus traditional 8-hour cycles. Rates can deviate significantly from CEXs, especially during volatile periods, creating arbitrage opportunities but also requiring careful risk management."},{"question":"What are the main costs when trading JUP perpetuals on Paradex?","answer":"Trading fees are 0.02% maker and 0.05% taker, plus StarkNet gas costs for transactions and potential bridging fees for deposits/withdrawals. The hourly funding payments add ongoing costs based on position direction and rate magnitude."},{"question":"Can I hedge JUP positions across multiple pairs on Paradex?","answer":"Currently, Paradex has minimal pair coverage limiting direct hedging options. Portfolio margin enables capital efficiency when multiple positions are held, but cross-asset hedging strategies are constrained by available trading pairs."},{"question":"What risks are unique to JUP trading on a StarkNet-based DEX?","answer":"Key risks include StarkNet network congestion affecting order execution, smart contract vulnerabilities inherent to DEX operations, and potential bridge delays when moving funds. These technical risks are additional to standard perpetual futures market risks."}]}]
